Welcome to notebook six of the Java track. The topic for this session is concurrency, and especially the brand new virtual threads that arrived in Java twenty one. Concurrency is the area where most production bugs live. Modern Java has made the easy cases dramatically easier, and virtual threads in particular change how you should think about concurrent code. But the hard cases, the ones involving shared mutable state, still demand care. We will walk the easy to hard ladder, one rung at a time.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, what a thread actually is, and why concurrency exists at all. Starting threads with the Thread class, and why you almost never do that in real code. The two task shapes, Runnable and Callable. The Executor Service framework, which is the pool based way to run tasks. The Future type for getting a result back from an asynchronous task. Then the headline feature. Virtual threads. What they are, how they differ from platform threads, and when to use each. The Completable Future type, for composing chains of asynchronous work. Structured concurrency, which is the preview feature that will reshape how Java concurrent code is written. The shared mutable state problem, and why the same field touched by two threads without coordination produces wrong results. The three ways to fix it. The synchronized keyword. The Reentrant Lock class for explicit locks. And the atomic variables for lock free updates. The concurrent collections like Concurrent Hash Map and Blocking Queue. And finally, a one paragraph tour of the volatile keyword and the java virtual machine memory model.

Let us start with the question, what is a thread. A thread is an independent path of execution inside a single process. One java virtual machine process can have many threads. Each thread runs its own sequence of instructions. The operating system multiplexes the threads across the available CPU cores. From the application's point of view, all the threads are running at the same time. From the hardware's point of view, only as many threads run truly in parallel as you have cores. The operating system scheduler decides which thread is on which core at each moment.

Why do we bother with threads at all. Two reasons. The first is latency. While one thread is waiting for the network or for the disk, other threads can keep working. The second is throughput. The java virtual machine can spread CPU bound work across multiple cores, so a four core machine can do four times the computation per second compared with a single thread.

Threads are essential. They are also the most common source of subtle bugs, because two threads accessing the same memory can interleave in surprising ways. Most of this notebook is about how to get the benefits without the bugs.

The lowest level way to start a thread in Java is to construct a Thread instance with a Runnable body, and call its start method. Do not confuse start with run. Start launches a new operating system thread that runs the body. Run executes the body on the current thread, which is almost never what you want. After you call start, you can call join on the thread to wait for it to finish.

You should almost never write new Thread in real Java code. There are several reasons. Creating an operating system thread is expensive. Each platform thread typically reserves about one megabyte of stack memory, plus kernel resources, and there is overhead for the operating system scheduler. There is no built in way to limit concurrency, so a loop that spawns threads can exhaust the operating system. There is no convenient way to get a result back from a Runnable, because run returns void. And there is no built in lifecycle management. You have to handle interruption, errors, and cleanup yourself. Use an Executor Service instead, which we will get to in a moment.

The two task shapes in modern Java are Runnable and Callable of V. Both represent a task to run on some thread, but they differ in what they return. Runnable's single method is called run. It returns void. It cannot throw checked exceptions. Callable of V's single method is called call. It returns a V. It can throw any exception, including checked ones. Use Runnable for fire and forget side effects, like writing to a log. Use Callable of V for tasks that compute a result you want to use, and that might fail with a checked exception.

An Executor Service is a managed pool of worker threads that you submit tasks to. The pool owns the threads. You just hand it work. This is the right abstraction for almost every concurrent workload you write in modern Java.

The Executors utility class is a factory of common pool shapes. The new Fixed Thread Pool method gives you a pool with a fixed number of threads, and queues excess tasks. The new Cached Thread Pool method gives you a pool that grows as needed and reuses idle threads. Do not use the cached pool for hostile or unbounded workloads, because it can spawn an unbounded number of threads. The new Single Thread Executor gives you exactly one worker, and tasks run sequentially through it. And the new Virtual Thread Per Task Executor, added in Java twenty one, spawns a fresh virtual thread per submitted task, with no thread sharing.

Always use try with resources around an executor service, or call shutdown explicitly. As of Java nineteen, Executor Service implements Auto Closeable. The close method waits for in flight tasks to complete and then shuts down the pool. If you forget this and the pool is still alive, its threads are non daemon by default, which prevents the java virtual machine from exiting cleanly.

When you submit a Callable to an executor service, you get back a Future. A Future is a placeholder for the result of an asynchronous computation, possibly not ready yet. The main methods on Future are get, get with a timeout, cancel, and is done. The get method blocks until the result is ready, then returns it. Get can throw two checked exceptions. Interrupted Exception, if the current thread is interrupted while waiting. And Execution Exception, if the task itself threw an exception, in which case the wrapped cause is accessible via get Cause.

Future is fine for submit and wait patterns. It does not compose well, however. There is no way to say with a Future, when this task finishes, do something else, without blocking a thread to wait. For composition we use Completable Future, which we will meet shortly.

Now the headline feature of modern Java. Virtual threads.

Until Java twenty one, every Java thread was what we now call a platform thread. A platform thread is a thin wrapper around an operating system thread. Operating system threads are expensive. Around one megabyte of stack memory each. Significant kernel scheduling overhead. About ten thousand of them in flight on a real machine before things start to fall apart. This is why thread pools existed at all. You could not afford to give every concurrent task its own platform thread.

Virtual threads change this. A virtual thread is a java virtual machine managed alternative to a platform thread. It is lightweight, measured in kilobytes rather than megabytes. The java virtual machine multiplexes many virtual threads onto a small pool of platform threads, which we call carriers. When a virtual thread blocks on input output, like a database call or a network read, the java virtual machine parks the virtual thread and the carrier moves on to run another virtual thread that is ready. When the input output completes, the parked virtual thread is woken up and continues on whichever carrier is available.

The practical effect is that you can have millions of concurrent virtual threads waiting on the network. Code that previously needed a non blocking framework like Netty, or a reactive library like Project Reactor, or async await gymnastics, can now just be written as plain, blocking, one thread per request code. And it scales. A web server with a virtual thread per request can handle hundreds of thousands of concurrent connections on commodity hardware, with no thread pool tuning required.

When to use virtual threads. Input output bound work. Hypertext transfer protocol servers. Database calls. Network clients. Anything that spends most of its time waiting. This is exactly the workload virtual threads were designed for.

When to use platform threads. CPU bound work. A virtual thread that never blocks just pins its carrier to itself and offers no benefit over a platform thread. For raw computation, a fixed thread pool sized to the CPU count is still the right answer.

One important thing not to do. Avoid the synchronized keyword on hot paths inside virtual threads. The synchronized keyword pins the virtual thread to its carrier for the duration of the synchronized block. While pinned, no other virtual thread can use that carrier, which defeats the lightweight model. Use Reentrant Lock instead, which we will see shortly. Reentrant Lock does not pin.

For composing chains of asynchronous work, the Completable Future type is the right tool. Future lets you wait for a result. Completable Future lets you chain what to do with it. The shape will be familiar from Promises in JavaScript, or Future in Scala.

There are three main combinators on Completable Future. The then Apply method takes a function from T to R, and transforms the result. It is like Stream dot map. The then Compose method takes a function from T to Completable Future of R, and chains another asynchronous step. It is like Stream dot flat map. It flattens nested futures. The then Combine method takes another Completable Future and a bi function, waits for both to complete, and merges their results.

Completable Future also has error handling combinators. The exceptionally method takes a function from throwable to T, and runs only if the future failed. It is the recovery branch. The handle method takes a bi function of value and error, and runs no matter what, so you can react to either outcome.

For coordinating many futures, the all Of static method takes a varargs of completable futures and returns a Completable Future of Void that completes when all of them complete. The any Of static method completes as soon as any one of the input futures completes.

Completable Future is powerful but easy to misuse. Orphaned tasks. Leaked threads. Errors that get lost in the chain. The next step in Java's concurrency story, currently in preview, is called structured concurrency. Structured concurrency treats a group of concurrent tasks as a single block. The tasks share a lifetime. Errors propagate up to the parent block. And the block cannot exit until every child has either finished or been cancelled. The shape echoes try with resources.

The structured model gives you three guarantees that the unstructured model did not. Tasks never outlive the block that started them. Errors never get swallowed. Cancellation propagates automatically. Treat structured concurrency as the future direction of concurrent Java. Once it is out of preview, you should prefer it over hand rolled Completable Future graphs for most use cases.

Now we shift from the easy side of concurrency to the hard side. The shared mutable state problem.

When two threads touch the same field without coordination, you get data races. A data race is an interleaving of operations that produces wrong results. Sometimes the wrong results show up deterministically. Sometimes they show up only one time in a million runs. The classic example is the increment operator. The expression value plus plus looks like one operation, but it compiles to three. Read the current value. Add one. Write the new value back. Two threads can both read the same value, both write back the same incremented number, and one update is silently lost. This is the canonical race condition.

There are three ways to fix shared mutable state, in increasing sophistication. Synchronization. Explicit locks. And atomic variables.

The simplest fix is the synchronized keyword. Every Java object has what is called an intrinsic lock. The synchronized keyword takes that lock for the duration of a block or method. Only one thread at a time can hold a given lock. Others block until the holder releases it. You can mark an entire method as synchronized, which locks the receiver, the this reference. Or you can use a synchronized block, which locks a specific object that you supply.

Synchronized is simple and built into the language, but it has limits. There is no timeout. There is no try lock. There is no fairness control. And critically for virtual threads, synchronized pins the virtual thread to its carrier, so it should be avoided on the hot path of virtual thread code.

For everything synchronized cannot do, reach for Reentrant Lock from the package java util concurrent locks. The semantics are the same. One holder at a time. But you get additional capabilities. The try lock method attempts to acquire the lock without blocking. The try lock with timeout method gives up after the timeout. The lock Interruptibly method releases the lock if the current thread is interrupted. And Reentrant Lock does not pin virtual threads, which makes it the right choice for virtual thread code.

The pattern for using Reentrant Lock is critical to get right. Call lock to acquire. Then immediately enter a try block. Do your work. Then in a finally block, call unlock. The finally ensures the lock is released even if the work throws an exception. Always release in a finally block.

There is also a Read Write Lock. It splits the lock into a read lock, which many threads can hold simultaneously, and a write lock, which only one thread can hold at a time. Use it for data structures where reads dominate writes, like a cache that is hit often but updated occasionally.

For a single value updated concurrently, the package java util concurrent atomic provides classes that are faster than any lock. The atomic classes use central processing unit level compare and swap instructions and never block. The most common are Atomic Integer, Atomic Long, Atomic Boolean, and Atomic Reference, the generic atomic wrapper for any reference type.

The atomic classes give you methods like increment and get, decrement and get, add and get, compare and set, update and get with a unary operator, and accumulate and get with a binary operator. Each of these executes atomically with respect to other threads, so there is no race.

The plain Hash Map and Array List from the collections framework are not thread safe. Concurrent modification of either gives undefined behaviour, often a Concurrent Modification Exception, but sometimes silent corruption. The package java util concurrent supplies thread safe replacements designed for high contention.

Concurrent Hash Map is the thread safe replacement for Hash Map. It uses fine grained locking internally, so different keys can be updated by different threads in parallel. It is also the right place to store concurrent counters, using the compute If Absent method to lazily insert an Atomic Integer per key, and then increment and get on the value.

Copy On Write Array List is a thread safe list that copies the underlying array on every write. It is appropriate when the read to write ratio is heavily skewed toward reads, because reads are lock free, but writes are linear in the size of the list.

Blocking Queue is the producer consumer hand off primitive. The put method on a blocking queue blocks if the queue is full. The take method blocks if the queue is empty. The two together let one or more producer threads feed work to one or more consumer threads without explicit synchronisation. Linked Blocking Queue is the standard implementation. Array Blocking Queue is the bounded variant.

Concurrent Linked Queue is a lock free first in first out queue. Use it when you need an unbounded concurrent queue with non blocking semantics.

Finally, one paragraph on the volatile keyword and the java virtual machine memory model. Without volatile, the compiler and the central processing unit are allowed to cache field reads in registers or in per core caches indefinitely. Two threads can disagree about the value of a plain field forever. The volatile keyword on a field forces every read to come from main memory and every write to flush to main memory. It establishes a happens before relationship between writes and reads of that field. Volatile does not, however, make compound operations atomic. A field declared volatile int x, with the line x plus plus, is still racy, because the increment compiles to read, add, write, and another thread can squeeze in between the read and the write. Use volatile for simple flags like a boolean shutdown signal that one thread sets and another reads. Reach for Atomic Integer or Atomic Reference whenever you actually need to update a value concurrently.

That wraps notebook six. You can now write concurrent Java with the right primitives. Virtual threads for input output bound services. Platform threads for central processing unit work. Atomic and concurrent utilities for shared state. Completable Future, or structured concurrency soon, for composing asynchronous work. Spring services lean on every primitive we just covered. Every Spring request handler runs on a thread. Every database call is a blocking operation that virtual threads make cheap. Every shared cache uses a concurrent hash map or similar under the hood.

Notebook seven turns to the runtime and the tooling that wraps everything we have built so far. The java virtual machine itself, including heap, stack, metaspace, and garbage collection at a glance. Reflection, and how it powers Spring's annotation driven model. Maven and Gradle, the two build tools that every Spring project uses. And JUnit five with Mockito, for testing.
